STYLESHEET.CSS
ul{                            
list-style: none;              /*get rid of bullets*/
padding: 0;
margin: 0;                     /*get rid of the padding and margin*/
}

ul li a{                       /*CSS rule to specify the path*/
text-decoration: none;         /*get rid of the underline*/
font-family: Georgia, "Times New Roman", Times;
background-color: #5c755e;     /*the background color is only sizing itself to the area of the text*/
color: white;
display: block;                /*convert the inline element to the blcok element (bg-color size)*/
width: 80px;
margin: 5px;                   /*make it more like a button*/
padding: 10px;                 /*it will increase the size of the buttons*/
border: 1px solid black;
border-radius: 2px;
text-align: center;
height: 25px;
line-height: 25px;             /*perfectly fvertical centered when the "line-height"="height".*/
}

ul li a:hover{                 /*HOVER OVER EFFECT*/
background-color: #d3d3d3;
color: black;
}



Notes:
<ul> is a kind of BLOCK element (top-down order).
<a> is a kind of INLINE element.
ul li a{}: we don't actually have to put these in here, we could actually just specify a{] for the anchor tag.
           But it's good practice to the paths in so that you kind of know the path.
